{
  "answer": "**Iqbal's \"Falsafa-e-Gham\" (Bang-E-Dara Part 3, Ch. 7)** presents sorrow (*gham*) not as a curse but as life's essential polish, awakening the soul and revealing its secrets. The speaker directly addresses grief as a transformative force: \"Through trials of Sorrow, human nature finds its grace, / The dust of anguish is a polish for the heart's own face.[^1] ... Sorrow is not sorrow, but a silent song of soul, / Embracing all the music that makes existence whole.\"\n\n**The Old English \"Resignation\" (Old English Elegies, Ch. 9)** is a personal lament of exile and hardship, where the speaker grieves lost homeland and friends but surrenders to divine will: \"my reward for love was always sorrow, as I have now lived it. / Yet it is best, when a man cannot change his Fate, / that he then endure it well.\"[^2]\n\n**Manusmṛti Book 12** frames suffering (*duḥkha*, torments) impersonally as the fruit of karma across rebirths—hells, vile wombs, diseases, separations—without a first-person speaker directly addressing personal grief. A representative verse on karmic woe: \"births in vile wombs, which are mostly full of suffering, always; and afflictions from cold and heat, and various kinds of fears.\"[^3] No stanza shows a speaker confronting \"their own grief,\" as the text is didactic, not lyrical.\n\n**Ranking by reconciliation** (acceptance/embrace of grief, from most to least):  \n1. **Iqbal**: Fully reconciles by philosophizing grief as soul-enriching music—active celebration.  \n2. **Resignation**: Reconciles via stoic endurance and faith in God/Fate—passive surrender.  \n3. **Manusmṛti**: Least personal; suffering is karmic inevitability to expiate, not addressed introspectively.\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, [\"Falsafa-e-Gham\"](https://falsafa.corpus/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/07-falsafa-e-gham/translation/#p-141d8d).\n\n[^2]: *Old English Elegies*, [\"Resignation\"](https://falsafa.corpus/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/09-resignation/translation/#p-04f5b1).\n\n[^3]: *Manusmṛti*, [Chapter 12](https://falsafa.corpus/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/12/translation/#p-76b0e8) (representative of karmic sufferings in Mn_12.77); no personal first-person grief-stanza exists.",
